As there was no postal system at that time, letters had to be sent by one's own messengers (tabellarii) or the messen- gers oi one's friends. This made the composition of a letter a more serious matter in Cicero’s day than it is in ours. But his letters were not always studied productioris: some ot them were written while he was traveling; others between the courses at dinner⁸3 and he writes to Cassius⁷: praeposteras habes tabellarias . . . cum a me discedunt, flagitant litteras . . . atque idipsum facerent commodius, si milri aliquid spati ad · scribemdum darent, sed petasati ueniunt, comites ad partam exspectare attunt.
